description: From Latin enatus (ēnātus) (from ēnāscor (“spring forth”)) + English  +‎ -ion.

entries.meaning: (botany) A small outgrowth on the surface of a plant organ.
examples: In field infections, the enations are very small and appear as gray streaks on the backs of the leaves. However, conspicuous enations appear on plants inoculated and reared in the glasshouse (Lindsten, 1961a; Catherall, 1970).

entries.meaning: (botany, uncountable) The generation of such an outgrowth.
